Grace Edema Wife of the Lagos State Governor, Dr. Ibijoke Sanwo-Olu, has unveiled three mobile chest X-ray vans to support tuberculosis screening, search and diagnosis. A statement on Tuesday explained that the mobile X-ray vans would be moving round the state to provide prompt chest x-ray services and effective diagnosis of TB. Speaking at the inauguration of the specialised vehicle at the Evans Square, Lagos Mainland Local Government Area, Sanwo-Olu said the mobile X-ray vans were acquired by the government to explore innovative, efficient and best practices in health care service delivery. “It is hoped that the introduction of this chest X-ray screening vans will bridge the gap of inadequate logistics for TB diagnosis, improve childhood TB diagnosis and ultimately bring TB diagnosis and care to the door steps of Lagosians. “A total of 38,277 TB cases were missed in Lagos State in 2019 and it is hoped that the introduction of Lagos TB Chest X-ray screening will drastically reduce the number of missed TB cases in subsequent years,” she said. The Commissioner for Health, Prof. Akin Abayomi, said the government would ensure that Lagosians were empowered to become responsible for their health and well-being. The director of Disease Control in the Lagos State Ministry of Health, Dr Rotimi Agbolagorite, said TB case notification which was 8,182 in 2010  and 9,750 in 2018  had increased to 11,723 cases in 2019. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com  